# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/1880-worcester-worcesters-season] The 1880 season was the first for the **Worcester Worcesters** franchise in the National League, having played 1879 in the National Association.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/1880-worcester-worcesters-season] The team finished its initial season with a 40–43 record, good for fifth place.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/1880-worcester-worcesters-season] Lee Richmond threw a perfect game on June 12, 1880, the first ever perfect game in Major League Baseball history in a 1–0 victory over the Cleveland Blues.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/1880-worcester-worcesters-season] On August 20, they became the first major-league team to be no-hit at home when Pud Galvin of the Buffalo Bisons defeated them, 1–0.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/1881-worcester-worcesters-season] The **1881 Worcester Worcesters** finished with a 32–50 record, last place in the National League.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/1882-worcester-worcesters-season] The **1882 Worcester Worcesters** finished with an 18–66 record, last place in the National League.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] An **agricultural show, county show** or **farm show** is a public event exhibiting the equipment, animals, sports and recreation associated with agriculture and animal husbandry.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] The largest comprise a **livestock show** (a judged event or display in which breeding stock is exhibited), a trade fair, competitions, and entertainment.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] The work and practices of farmers, animal fanciers, cowboys, and zoologists may be displayed.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] The terms *agricultural show* and *livestock show* are synonymous with the North American terms **county fair** and **state fair**, and the UK **county show**.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Agricultural shows tend to be important events for sharing different agricultural practices or techniques, learning about new technologies or celebrating achievements by producers through competitions.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] The first known agricultural show was held by Salford Agricultural Society, Lancashire, in 1768.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Since the 19th century, agricultural shows have provided local people with an opportunity to celebrate achievements and enjoy a break from day-to-day routine.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] With a combination of serious competition and light entertainment, annual shows acknowledged and rewarded the hard work and skill of primary producers and provided a venue for rural families to socialise.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] City shows also provide city people with an opportunity to engage directly with rural life and food production.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Agriculture shows are often enlivened with competitive events, including sheaf tossing, show jumping, food competitions, and tent pegging.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Demolition derbies and rodeos are popular in the US and campdrafting and wood chopping are often held in Australia.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Studs are generally available for a fee.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] A livestock show is an event where livestock are exhibited and judged on certain phenotypical breed traits as specified by their respective breed standard.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Species of livestock that may be shown include pigs, cattle, sheep, goats, horses, rabbits, llamas, and alpacas.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Poultry such as chickens, geese, ducks, turkeys, and pigeons are also shown competitively.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] There are also competitive shows for dogs, sheepdogs, and cats.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Prize-winners at agricultural shows are generally awarded inscribed medals, cups, rosettes or ribbons.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] The National Museum of Australia has a rare collection of medals documenting the history of agricultural shows and rural industries across Australia.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] The 111 medals range in date from the mid-19th to the early 20th century and many are associated with significant individuals and organizations.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] In the United States, agricultural fairs are a significant exposure source for swine influenza.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Certain strains of swine influenza can be transmitted from pig to pig, pig to human, and human to human; swine influenza infection does not always show signs of illness.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Related to a show is the "field day", with elements of a trade show for machinery, equipment and skills required for broadacre farming.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Field days typically do not involve livestock, show bags or sideshows, but may include events such as ploughing competitions not usually associated with shows due to the larger space required.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] In some communities in northern England Field Days (or Club Days) have lost their agricultural character and have become community celebrations.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] The events are good sources of agricultural information, as organizers can arrange for guest speakers to talk on a range of topics, such as the talk on the yellow-flowering alfalfa at the South Dakota field day.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] A Landcare survey conducted in 1992/93 revealed that field days in Australia have a high value among local farmers.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] New Zealand's National Agricultural Fieldays is held annually in June at Mystery Creek, near Hamilton, New Zealand, and attracts 1,000 exhibitors and over 115,000 visitors through its gates.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/agricultural-show] Smaller agricultural shows, held annually in New Zealand's towns and communities, are generally called "agricultural and pastoral shows" ("A&P shows").
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] A **ballpark**, or **baseball park**, is a type of sports venue where baseball is played.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The playing field is divided into two field sections called the infield and the outfield.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The infield is an area whose dimensions are rigidly defined in part based on the placement of bases, and the outfield is where dimensions can vary widely from ballpark to ballpark.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] A larger ballpark may also be called a **baseball stadium** because it shares characteristics of other stadiums.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] A baseball field can be referred to as a diamond.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The infield is a rigidly structured diamond of dirt and grass containing the three bases, home plate, and the pitcher's mound.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The space between the bases and home is normally a grass surface, save for the dirt mound in the center.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Some ballparks have grass or artificial turf between the bases, and dirt only around the bases and pitcher's mound.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Others, such as Koshien Stadium in Hyōgo Prefecture, Japan, have an infield of entirely dirt.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Two white lines extend from the home plate area, aligned with the first and third bases.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] These are the *foul lines* or *base lines*, usually differentiated by referring to them as the first base line, or the third base line.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] If a ball hit by the batter lands outside of the space between these two lines or rolls out of this space before reaching first or third base, the ball is "foul" (meaning it is dead and the play is over).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] If it lands between or on the lines, it is "fair".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] At the end of the lines are two foul poles, which help the umpires judge whether a ball is fair or foul.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] These "foul poles" are actually in fair territory, so a ball that hits them on the fly is a home run (if hit on the bounce, it is instead an automatic double).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] On either side of home plate are the two batter's boxes (left-handed and right-handed.) This is where the batter stands when at bat.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Behind home is the catcher's box, where the catcher and the home plate umpire stand.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Next to the first and third base are two coaches' boxes, where the first and third base coaches guide the baserunners, generally with gestures or shouts.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] As the baserunner faces away from the outfield when running from second base to third, they cannot see where the ball is and must look to the third base coach on whether to run, stop, or slide.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Farther from the infield on either side are the dugouts, where the teams and coaches sit when they're not on the field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] They are named such because, at the professional levels, this seating is below the level of the playing field to not block the view from prime spectator seating locations.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] In amateur parks, the dugouts may be above-ground wooden or CMU structures with seating inside, or simply benches behind a chain-link fence.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Beyond the infield and between the foul lines is a large grass outfield, generally twice the depth of the infield.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The playing field is bordered by fences of varying heights.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The infield fences are in foul territory, and a ball hit over them is not a home run; consequently, they are often lower than the outfield fences to provide a better view for spectators.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Sometimes, the outfield fence is made higher in certain areas to compensate for close proximity to the batter.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] In many parks, the field is surrounded by an area roughly 10 feet (3.0 m) wide made of dirt or rubberized track surface called a "warning track".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] In the 1937 refurbishment of the original Yankee Stadium, a running track that ran the perimeter of the field was incorporated into the field of play as the first warning track.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] MLB formalized the warning track as a requirement in 1949.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Beyond the outfield fence in professional parks is an area called the batter's eye.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] To ensure the batter can see the white ball, the batter's eye contains no seating and is darker in color.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The batter's eye area can be anything from a dark wall to a grassy slope.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Most major league ballparks are oriented with the central axis (home plate through second base through center field) of the playing field running toward the north or east or some direction between.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Major League Baseball Rule 1.04 states that it is "desirable" (but not required) that the central axis run east-northeast (about 22 degrees north of east).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] This is to prevent the setting sun from being in the batter's eyes.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] In practice, major league parks vary up to about 90 degrees from east-northeast in either direction, but none face west, except for a few which are oriented just slightly west of straight north.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] (Left-handed pitchers are called "southpaws", and indeed the pitcher's left hand is toward the south in the usual park layout, and this has often been cited as the source of the appellation.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Today, in Major League Baseball, a multi-tiered seating area, a grandstand, surrounds the infield.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] How far this seating extends down the baselines or around the foul poles varies from park to park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] In minor league parks, the grandstands are notably smaller, proportional to expected sizes of crowds compared with the major leagues.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The seating beyond the outfield fence generally differs from the grandstand, though some multi-purpose or jewel box parks have the grandstand surround the entire field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] This area could contain inexpensive bleacher seats, smaller grandstands, or simply inclined seating.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] In local ballparks, there are often simply a set or two of aluminum bleachers on the first-base and third-base sides.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Distinctive from "goal games" such as football and basketball, which have fixed-size playing areas, the infield is the only rigidly laid-out part of the field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Like its English relative, cricket, there is significant flexibility in the shape and size of the rest of the playing area.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Baseball leagues may specify a minimum distance from home plate to the outfield fences.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Generally, the higher the skill level, the deeper the minimum dimensions must be, to prevent an excess of home runs.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] In the major leagues, a rule was passed in 1958 that compelled any new fields built after that point to have a minimum distance of 325 feet (99 m) from home plate to the fences in left and right field, and 400 feet (120 m) to center.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] This rule was passed to avoid situations like the Los Angeles Coliseum, which was 251 ft (77 m). down the left field line.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] However, with the opening of Baltimore's Camden Yards (1992), the "minimum distance" rule began to be ignored.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] One factor may be that the quaint, "retro" look of Camden Yards, with its irregular measurements, proved to be very popular, along with a traditionalist backlash against the symmetrical, multi-purpose, "cookie-cutter" stadiums.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Since the opening of Camden Yards, many other "retro" stadiums have been built, each with asymmetrical fences.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] These distances vary from park to park, and can even change drastically in the same park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] One of the most famous examples is the original Yankee Stadium, whose odd-shaped plot of land caused right field to be over 100 feet (30 m) shorter than left, although this difference lessened over time.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The rectangular Polo Grounds had extremely short distance down the lines, 258 ft (79 m). to right and 280 ft (85 m). to left.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] In contrast, the deepest part of center field was nearly 500 ft (150 m). from home plate.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Older ballparks, such as Fenway Park, were grandfathered in and allowed to keep their original dimensions.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Also, new parks have sometimes received special dispensation to deviate from these rules.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] For instance, the second Yankee Stadium, built 2009, used the same dimensions as the original Yankee Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The heights of the fences can also vary greatly, the most famous example being the 37-foot (11 m)-high Green Monster in Fenway Park's left field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Such tall fences are often used to stop easy home runs in a section of the ballpark where the distances from home are shorter, or where there is little space between the field and the street beyond.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Some in-play scoreboards and high fences reached 50 to 60 feet (18 m), whereas a few outfields were even lined with hedges rather than normal fences or walls.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Humphrey Metrodome, when set up for baseball, had a 23-foot (7.0 m) right field "fence" that was actually a relatively thin blue plastic sheet covering folded up football seats.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] It was often called a "baggie" or "Hefty bag".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Some ballparks have irregularly shaped fences.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Ballparks may have round swooping fences or rigidly angled fences, or possibly a significant change in direction or irregular angle.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] For example, the center field stands and the left field stands at Fenway Park meet at an uneven angle, creating an indentation (called "the triangle") that angles sharply back into the stands.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] In Citi Field and Oracle Park, part of the right field fence juts unevenly into the outfield as if the builders were trying to create an unpredictable ricochet effect for balls hit against it.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Some "retro" parks, such as Globe Life Park in Arlington, throw in a sudden and small inward turn (often referred to as a jog) just to give a little quirkiness to the design.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Milwaukee's Miller Park was designed, with the help of former player Robin Yount, to promote extra base hits.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Originally (mostly in the old jewel box parks) these variations resulted from the shape of the property where the park was constructed.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] If there was a street beyond left field, the distance to the left field fence would be shorter, and if the distance was too short, the fence would be higher.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] For example, in the old Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C., part of center field had to be built around a cluster of apartment houses and the result was a rather large angular indentation in the left-center field fence.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Now, these variations are mostly influenced by the specifications and whims of the designers.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] New "retro" parks, which try to recapture the feel of the jewel box parks, are often designed to have these quirks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Baseball was originally played in open fields or public parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The genesis of modern baseball is conventionally connected with Elysian Fields in Hoboken, New Jersey, a large public park where the businessmen of New York City gathered from time to time to play organized baseball games and cricket matches, starting around the mid-1840s.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The name "Field" or "Park" was typically attached to the names of the early ballparks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] With the beginnings of professional baseball, the ballfield became part of a complex including fixed spectator seating areas, and an enclosure to restrict access to paying customers, as with a fairgrounds.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The name "Grounds" began to be attached to ballparks, starting with the Union Grounds in 1862.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The suffixes "Field" and "Park" were still used, but many professional ballparks were "Grounds".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The last major league "Grounds" was the Polo Grounds in New York City, which was razed in 1964.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The term "stadium" has been used since ancient times, typically for a running track and its seating area.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] As college football gained in popularity, the smaller college playing fields and running tracks (which also frequently had the suffix "Field") gave way to large stadiums, many of them built during the sport's "boom" of the 1920s.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Major league baseball enjoyed a similar boom.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] One of the first major league ballparks to be called a "stadium" was actually the Polo Grounds, which was temporarily renamed Brush Stadium from its reconstruction in 1911 until the death of owner John T.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] By then, the most famous baseball "stadium" of them all had been constructed: Yankee Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] From that point until the retro building boom of the 1990s, the suffix "Stadium" was used for almost every new major league venue, and was sometimes applied to the old ones, such as Shibe Park, which was renamed Connie Mack Stadium in 1954.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The suffix "Dome" was also used for the indoor stadiums constructed from the 1960s onward.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The retro era of the 1990s and early 2000s saw some venues return to using "park" in a stadium's name, even in domed structures such as T-Mobile Park and American Family Field (which opened with the name Miller Park).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] There is little consistency in the choice between "Field" and "Park".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] For example, Houston's Daikin Park was originally named "Enron Field".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Seating area design of stadiums is affected by many variables, including required capacity, audience access, and road traffic.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Early ballparks like Elysian Fields were a far distance from the city center.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Each game was an event, and fans traveled by public transit to watch the game.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] With the growth of professional leagues, and consequent growth in the quantity of games, each game became less of an event, and fan convenience became more important.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Many professional ballparks were built either near the city center, or in working-class neighborhoods, based on the expected economic level of the average fan.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Consequently, the classic ballparks typically had little space for automobiles, as it was expected that most fans would take mass transit to the games, a situation that still prevails at Boston's Fenway Park and Chicago's Wrigley Field, for example.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Some early ballparks, such as Brooklyn's Eastern Park, were abandoned because the trolley lines did not go out far enough and the team was not performing well enough for people to tolerate the inconvenience.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] As fans became more affluent, and especially as they moved to the suburbs and bought cars, the lack of parking became an important issue.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Some ballparks remedied this problem through the construction of parking garages in the vicinity, or building new ballparks with ample parking.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] Others built ballparks in the suburbs, typically with large parking areas.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The ballpark/stadium thus became an "island" in an "ocean" of parking space.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p01] The modern "retro" trend strives to support multiple modes of transport, by having an urban location with available parking and accessibility by public transport.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The first professional baseball venues were large **wooden ballparks** with seats mounted on wood platforms.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Although known for being constructed out of wood, they featured iron columns for better support.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Some included one tier of inclined seating, topped with either a flat roof or, in some instances, a small upper tier.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The outfield was bordered by tall walls or fences covered in advertisements, much like today's minor league parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] These advertisements were sometimes fronted with bleacher seats, or "bleaching boards".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Wood, while prone to decomposition, was a relatively inexpensive material.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] However, the use of wood as the primary material presented a major problem, especially as baseball continued to thrive.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Over time, the wooden stands aged and dried.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Many parks caught fire, and some were leveled completely.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] This problem, along with the popularization of baseball and expectations for long-term use of the parks were major factors that drove the transition to the new standard materials for ballparks: steel and concrete.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Some famous wooden parks, such as the Polo Grounds III in New York and National League Park in Philadelphia, burned and were rebuilt with fire-resistant materials (Polo Grounds IV and Baker Bowl).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Others were simply abandoned in favor of new structures built elsewhere.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] These new fire-resistant parks often lasted for many decades, and (retrospectively) came to be known as "jewel boxes".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] There are no more professional ballparks in existence left with this architectural trend, with the last one, Oriole Park V, burning down in 1944.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The earliest ballparks built or rebuilt of reinforced concrete, brick, and steel are now known as the **jewel box ballparks** or **classic parks**.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Two-tiered grandstands became much more prevalent in this era, as well.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The Baker Bowl in Philadelphia, which opened in 1895, was the first to use steel and brick as the primary construction materials and included a cantilevered upper deck seating area that hung out over the lower seating area.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Although it did not use reinforced concrete in its construction, Baker Bowl is considered the first of the jewel box parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The first to use reinforced concrete was Shibe Park, which opened in 1909, also in Philadelphia.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The upper decks were typically held up by steel pillars that obstructed the view from some seats in the lower level.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] However, because of the supports used, the upper decks could come very close to the field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The two-tiered design was the standard for decades, until the New York Yankees built Yankee Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] To accommodate the large crowds Babe Ruth drew, Yankee Stadium was built with three tiers.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] This became the new standard until some recently built parks reverted to two, including PNC Park in 2001.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Most jewel box parks were built to fit the constraints of actual city blocks, often resulting in significantly asymmetrical outfield dimensions and large outfield walls to prevent easy home runs.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Notable examples included League Park in Cleveland, which had a 40-foot (12 m)-tall wall in right field, and the Green Monster, the 37-foot (11 m)-tall left field wall at Fenway Park in Boston.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Notable exceptions include Shibe Park and Comiskey Park, which were built on rectangular city blocks that were large enough to accommodate symmetrical left and right fields.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Other sports, such as soccer and football, were often played at these sites (Yankee Stadium, for example, was designed to accommodate football).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] In contrast to the later multi-purpose parks, the seats were generally angled in a configuration suitable for baseball.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The "retro" ballparks built in the 1990s and beyond are an attempt to capture the feel of the jewel box parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The only jewel box parks still used by Major League Baseball are Fenway Park and Wrigley Field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] From the 1960s until the arrival of retro parks in 1992, baseball built many **multi-purpose ballparks**.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Also derisively known as "concrete donuts", "cookie-cutters", or "giant ashtrays", they were usually tall and circular or square structures made entirely of, usually bare, reinforced concrete.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The parks were built to hold baseball, but also were able to host other sports, such as football and soccer.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] One of the earliest baseball stadiums that incorporated this type of design was Cleveland Stadium (built 1932), which featured an oval grandstand that was more friendly to goal-centered sports like football.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] A park built to suit all sports well, which was co-owned by the teams or the city, seemed advantageous to all, especially because it was less expensive to maintain one stadium rather than two.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Some parks that were originally built for one sport were renovated to accommodate multiple sports.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The shape of the parks generally depended on the original use.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Ballparks that were renovated to accommodate football, like Candlestick Park and Anaheim Stadium, were usually asymmetrically shaped.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Football stadiums that were renovated to accommodate baseball, like Sun Life Stadium and Mile High Stadium, were usually of a rectangular shape, though Mile High actually started its life in 1948 as a Minor League Baseball park known as Bears Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Parks that were built to serve both were usually circular and completely enclosed on all sides.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] These were the parks that gained multi-purpose parks the reputation as bland cookie-cutter structures.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The first of these parks was DC Stadium (renamed RFK Stadium in 1969) in the District of Columbia.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] RFK is unique in that it hosted two different baseball teams, and that it was the first to *originally* be intended for multiple sports.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] A notable variant among the cookie-cutter stadia was Shea Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Its grandstand extended just beyond the foul poles and did not completely enclose the field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Plans were made to enclose the grandstand and build a dome, but engineers discovered that the structure could not handle the load of the proposed dome.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Thus, the area behind the outfield fence remained open.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] One major innovation of the multi-purpose parks was the cantilevered upper deck.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] In earlier ballparks, the columns used to support the upper decks obstructed the view from some seats in the lower deck.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] In the new design, the upper decks were extended upwards and the columns were removed.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] However, even though the extension counterbalanced some of the weight, the upper decks could no longer extend as close to the field and had to be moved back.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Also, the roofs could no longer be as large, and often only covered the top 15 or so rows.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Besides the drawbacks of the cantilever design, there were other issues with these parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] With few exceptions, seating was angled to face the center of the field of play, rather than home plate.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The furthest seats in these parks were 500 feet (150 m) or more from the plate.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The capacities of these stadiums were larger than previous baseball stadiums.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Typical game attendance did not fill the stadiums.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Due to the rectangular shape needed for football or soccer, outfield dimensions were generally symmetrical, and even seats at field level down the lines could be far from the action.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Multi-purpose stadiums also posed issues for their non-baseball tenants.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The "cookie-cutters" with swiveling, field-level sections proved problematic.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Because the front rows were too close to the field, the fans had difficulty seeing over the football benches.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] This was evident in the movable seating sections in RFK Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The first ten rows of the football configuration were practically at field level, and fans in those sections often stood up on their seats to get a better view.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Other stadiums overcame this simply by covering those seats, not bothering to sell them.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Despite being cost-effective, these problems eventually caused the parks to become unfashionable.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The multi-purpose architecture reached a climax when Toronto's SkyDome (now Rogers Centre) opened in 1989.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] It had state-of-the-art amenities including a retractable roof, hotel, and a restaurant behind the outfield from where patrons could view the games.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Rogers Centre was renovated into a baseball only stadium from 2022 to 2024.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] There are no more purely multi-purpose parks still in use today, with the Oakland Coliseum having been the last one in use.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The Athletics moved out of Oakland Coliseum in 2024 and will play at West Sacramento's Sutter Health Park for three seasons as a new dedicated facility of their own is built in Las Vegas.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Their former co-tenants, the NFL Oakland Raiders, moved to Las Vegas in 2020 and into Allegiant Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] An important type of ballpark is the **indoor park**.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] These parks are covered with a fixed roof, usually a hard concrete dome.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The reasons to build indoor parks are varied.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The Astrodome, the first indoor sports stadium ever built, was built to escape the hot and very humid climate of Houston and the Kingdome was built to escape Seattle's constant fall and winter rains.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] In Japan, domed stadiums were built to escape frequently rainy climates, as well as extreme snowfall in Sapporo.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] There is little to no natural light in these parks, necessitating the use of one of the most distinguishing aspects of an indoor park: artificial turf.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Since there was not enough light to grow grass, artificial turf is installed, and this affected the game.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Artificial turf is harder, and thus a ball hit on the ground moves faster and bounces higher.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] This, coupled with the usually dull white or gray roofs that could camouflage a fly ball, causing what Twins fans called a "dome-field advantage".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] A park of note is Olympic Stadium in Montreal.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The park was designed with a large tower that loomed over top.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Cables came down from the top of the tower to connect to the large oval center of the roof.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] This oval center was supposed to be lifted by the cables, opening the park up if the weather was pleasant.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] However, the mechanism never worked correctly, and what was supposed to be a retractable roof was initially not used, then used for only a short period of time, and later replaced with a permanently fixed roof, making the stadium a strictly indoor facility.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Humphrey Metrodome in Minneapolis, which instead of a rigid masonry roof was covered by inflatable fiberglass sheeting, held up by air pressure.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] A drawback to this design, at least in Minnesota's severe winter climate, was revealed when the dome collapsed three times in its first three years of operation due to accumulated snow.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The Tokyo Dome has a similar roof; due to Tokyo's considerably milder winter climate, that stadium has not had the Metrodome's snow-related issues.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The first generation of indoor parks faced many of the same problems of the multi-purpose parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Tropicana Field is the only indoor-only or fixed-dome park built specifically for baseball and the only one left hosting a Major League Baseball team, and is scheduled to be replaced in the near future.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The new ballpark for the Las Vegas Athletics is slated to have a fixed roof with a window to allow natural light in, like Allegiant Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Japan still has several fixed-dome parks designed primarily for baseball.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] One of these, the Sapporo Dome, features two separate playing surfaces.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Baseball is played on a permanently installed artificial surface within the dome, while a permanent grass pitch is attached to the structure and mechanically slid into the dome for use in soccer matches.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Also used by the Hanshin Tigers for season openers and August home games when their normal home of Koshien Stadium is being used for national high school tournaments.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Occasionally used by two other NPB teams, the Kintetsu Buffaloes and Orix BlueWave (now merged into the Orix Buffaloes).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] While most teams turned to multi-purpose parks, some built baseball-only parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] While these **modern ballparks** shirked some of the conventions of multi-purpose parks, they did include some of the new features.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The most notable influences were the cantilevered upper decks, the use of seating colors other than green, fairly plain concrete exteriors, and symmetrical outfields.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] While the multi-purpose parks have become all but extinct, some modern parks, such as Dodger Stadium and Kauffman Stadium, have been hailed for aging beautifully.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Rather than build new parks, the teams have decided instead to renovate the current structures, adding a few newer conveniences.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Several of the modern parks built as such have remained in use, with no indication of being demolished.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] While Cleveland Stadium is the ancestor to the multi-purpose ballpark, the ancestor of the modern ballpark is Milwaukee County Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] It was the first to feature a symmetrical, round outfield fence.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] It also featured the rounded V-shaped grandstand and colorful seats that are common among modern parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Coincidentally, it would have been one of the earlier examples of a converted park as well.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] It was supposed to replace a minor league facility, and serve as home of the minor league team until a major league franchise could be lured to the city.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] However, the Braves came to Milwaukee earlier than expected, and the minor league team never played in the stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The first two truly modern ballparks were built by the two New York teams who moved to California, the Giants and the Dodgers.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Candlestick Park was created first, but was converted to a multi-purpose park to accommodate the 49ers.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Dodger Stadium has been upgraded a number of times, but remains baseball-only and its original design is still largely intact.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Anaheim Stadium, which was initially modeled closely on Dodger Stadium, was expanded for football, but once the Rams departed, most of the extra outfield seating was peeled back, returning the structure to something closer to its original design.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The original Yankee Stadium is an exceptional case.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Yankee Stadium was originally built as a jewel box park, albeit a very large one.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] It was showing its age in the 1970s, and the stadium was extensively renovated during 1973–1975, converting it into more of a modern style ballpark.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Many of the characteristics that defined it as a classical jewel box were retained, so the remodeled Stadium straddled both categories.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Rogers Centre, which has a retractable roof and Tropicana Field, which has a fixed roof, can also be considered modern ballparks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Originally built as a multi-purpose stadium, Rogers Centre has been renovated as a baseball only park, while Tropicana Field was built with the intent to attract an MLB team to the Tampa Bay area.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] New Comiskey Park (now Rate Field) was the last modern ballpark to be built in North America.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] A series of renovations have been made to make it appear more like a retro-classic ballpark.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] Although they were purposefully built for baseball, some of these stadiums also hosted professional soccer and football teams at times.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] The Minnesota Vikings played at Metropolitan Stadium during the Twins' entire tenure there, and the Green Bay Packers played a few home games at Milwaukee County Stadium every year from 1953 through 1994.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p02] A few of them, including Metropolitan Stadium, also hosted NASL teams during the 1970s.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The indoor parks were built for several different reasons, chief among those weather.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] However, as multi-purpose parks became unfashionable, so did indoor parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] This led to the creation of **retractable-roof parks**.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] These allowed shelter from the elements, but still could be open when the weather was pleasant.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] To be able to support the roof, most were closed in on all sides like multi-purpose and indoor parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Because the roof needs to go somewhere when not covering the field, a distinguishing characteristic of the retractable roof park is a large extension of the interior spaces to either one side of the field or both sides that the roof sits on when retracted.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The only exception to this is American Family Field, whose fan-shaped roof folds in upon itself and hangs behind the stands down the foul lines.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Often, when retracted, the roof still hangs over the field, casting large shadows.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] This is countered at American Family Field by large panes of glass under the roof.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] While most stadiums seal up when the roof is closed, others remain partially open, such as T-Mobile Park, whose roof acts as an "umbrella" to shield from Seattle's frequently rainy weather.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Pittsburgh's Civic Arena was the first sports building in the world with a retractable roof; however, the building was originally constructed for the Pittsburgh Civic Light Opera, which moved out in 1969 due to dissatisfaction with the acoustics in the arena.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The arena's long-term tenants, the NHL's Pittsburgh Penguins, never played with the roof open, and the arena itself was never used for baseball (and was too small to be used for that sport).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] While Montreal's Olympic Stadium was the first baseball park to have a retractable roof, the roof was plagued by numerous problems, and was never fully used.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] This made Rogers Centre the first fully functional retractable-roof park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] It managed to succeed where Olympic Stadium failed, building a multi-section roof that folded upon itself, retracting over the hotel in center field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Retractable-roof parks can vary greatly in style, from the utilitarian (Rogers Centre), to those infused with retro elements (such as Daikin Park), to the contemporary (loanDepot Park).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The style of each park reflects the popular architecture of the era in which it was built.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] (This differs from indoor ballparks, all of which were built during the time of multi-purpose parks, and thus reflected the same "flying-saucer" style.) When Rogers Centre opened in 1989, baseball was near the end of the modern and multi-purpose era.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Chase Field, T-Mobile Park, Daikin Park, and American Family Field all opened in the middle of the retro era.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] When loanDepot Park opened in 2012 as Marlins Park, it introduced a new and different style, and perhaps the beginning of a new era.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The Texas Rangers built Globe Life Field in the retro style similar to their previous ballpark, Globe Life Park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Therefore, the term "retractable-roof ballpark/stadium" is not a description of the overall architectural style of the building, but of the functional aspect of it.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] For this reason, retractable-roof parks are also dual-listed in style-based types of ballparks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] For example, the four retractable-roof parks built in the United States during the retro era are also considered to be retro-modern ballparks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] HOK Sport, now known as Populous, designed Sahlen Field in Buffalo to attract a major league franchise to the city.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] HOK Sport would take what they learned in Buffalo about styling a **retro-classic ballpark**, or **retro/jewel box ballpark**, to their major league project in Baltimore.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] In 1992, Oriole Park at Camden Yards opened in Baltimore in a similar style and colour to a jewel box park, but with more features and accommodations.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The ballpark also has a modern, stepped-deck layout, columns removed, and fencing changed.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Since Camden Yards opened, two-thirds of all major league teams have opened new ballparks, each of which contain unique features.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The most important feature was that they were built primarily for baseball, although these venues have also hosted football, soccer and ice hockey games.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Turner Field was originally constructed as Centennial Olympic Stadium for the 1996 Summer Olympics and was retrofitted to baseball the following year.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Rate Field was the last modern park built in 1991 and was viewed as obsolete a year after opening.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The White Sox responded with a series of retro-classic style renovations, such as roofing changes, asymmetrical fencing, and a dark green colour scheme.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Upper deck seating was also reduced to eliminate less purchased seating locations.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The most recent retro-classic ballparks were built in New York City.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Queens' Citi Field is modeled after Ebbets Field, and the Bronx's Yankee Stadium is modeled after the pre-renovation "House that Ruth Built".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Teams are now trending away from the retro-classic look and are instead building retro-modern and contemporary ballparks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Turner Field was the first retro-classic park replaced, as the Atlanta Braves moved to Truist Park in 2017, while the Texas Rangers moved from Globe Life Park in Arlington to the retractable-roof Globe Life Field in 2020.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Rate Field is planned to be replaced with a new ballpark in the near future.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] While Camden Yards influenced nearly every ballpark built after it, not all fully adhere to its design.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Those that deviate to incorporate more modern-looking elements are called **retro-modern ballparks**.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Progressive Field, originally Jacobs Field, was built two years after Camden Yards, and featured the angular, asymmetrical fences of varying heights, a smaller upper deck, stepped tiers, and an unobtrusive singular color scheme.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] While the interior has all the hallmarks of a retro park, the exterior did not feature the look of the jewel box parks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] It could not truly be called a retro-classic park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Many of today's parks have followed in this second school of retro.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Rather than brick, the exteriors heavily feature white- or gray-painted steel.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] If there is any masonry, it is sandstone or limestone.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Some feature progressive elements such as curtain walls, or retractable roofs.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Angel Stadium has seen many changes throughout the years.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] It was originally a modern park, similar to the Angels' previous home, Dodger Stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] When the NFL's Los Angeles Rams left the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum in 1980 and set up shop in what was then Anaheim Stadium, the first round of renovations began.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The grandstand was expanded to completely enclose the stadium, turning it into a multi-purpose park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The Rams left in 1994, leaving the Angels alone in the large, 65,000-seat stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] After a two-year renovation, the steel was painted green, and what concrete remained was painted sandstone, including the sweeping curve of the entrance plaza.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The seating configuration was significantly altered, most notably by tearing out most of the outfield seating except for parts of the lower decks in left and right fields, to more closely resemble the original design from the park's first 15 years.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The finished product in 1998 was a retro-modern ballpark.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] In the same year, Chase Field opened as Bank One Ballpark for the expansion Arizona Diamondbacks, it incorporated a retractable roof and a swimming pool—elements that did not exist in jewel-box ballparks.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Despite the absence of MLB history in the Phoenix area and an overwhelming roof design, much of the interior was still built with all of the hallmarks of retro, similar to Progressive Field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Although Chase Field was not the first retractable-roof ballpark in history, it was the first in a wave of four retractable-roof ballparks (opening within just four years) to follow the retro-modern pattern.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] During the second decade of retro, Petco Park and Kauffman Stadium followed the construction and renovation concepts of Progressive Field and Angel Stadium, respectively.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Meanwhile, the period saw another subset of three new retro-modern stadiums that pushed away from classic parks even more.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] When Great American Ball Park opened in 2003, it featured a contemporary-looking, glass-wrapped facade.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Such prominent use of elements that were unfamiliar even to pre-1992 modern stadiums signaled that some stadium planners were more willing to incorporate designs that looked into the 21st century as much as they did the 20th.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Five years later, Nationals Park built off Cincinnati's design, making yet more liberal use of glass along with white concrete that would not clash with architecture in the District.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Nationals Park became the first stadium to go green while still offering all of the amenities—another concept that looked ahead instead of behind.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The retro-modern style climaxed in 2010 with the sculptured, contemporary exterior and canopy of Target Field, rendering it almost unrecognizable from the outside.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Its cantilevered glass on top of a limestone base was designed partly to functionally fit the tiny 8-acre plot in the middle of a bustling transportation interchange.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] But the principal architect of Target Field, Earl Santee of Populous, said that the exterior was also an artistic interpretation of the culture of Minnesotans: a dichotomy of cosmopolitan and natural.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Designing the building as a metaphor for people was a different way of thinking about ballpark architecture.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Subsequent retro-contemporary ballparks transitioned away from the architectural characteristics of both jewel-box and modern-style stadiums.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] While these venues incorporate contemporary amenities and field layouts, they maintain traditional aesthetic elements.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Characteristic retro-style features include asymmetrical outfield fences and monochromatic color schemes, frequently utilizing forest green.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Prior to the start of the 2012 baseball season, *USA Today* noted that new Marlins Park would "perhaps provide a coda to the postmodern Camden Yards era".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] After two decades of the retro style dominating ballpark architecture, a new type of design emerged in 2012 with the opening of the venue now known as LoanDepot Park, snapping the consecutive streak of 20 new (plus 3 renovated) MLB retro stadiums.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] This latest style's purpose is to make the fan experience the present-day culture of the stadium's surrounding city or area, and rejects the basic notion of retro.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Es Con Field Hokkaido, a ballpark in a similar style built for the Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters of Nippon Professional Baseball, opened in 2023.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The new ballpark for the Las Vegas Athletics was purposely designed to fit into the atmosphere of the surrounding Las Vegas Strip.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The expansion teams of the 1960s led to the emergence of two distinct subsets of parks in the major leagues: **temporary ballparks** and **converted ballparks**.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Temporary ballparks were used when a new ballpark was planned for an expansion team or moving franchise, but was not completed.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] This occurred for a few reasons, such as delays or a desire to hold off until the deal is settled.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] In this case, an established building is used as a temporary home, often a minor league park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] The first temporary ballparks were not actually used by expansion teams but by established franchises.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] When the Dodgers and Giants moved to California from New York, they played in Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum and Seals Stadium respectively while Dodger Stadium and Candlestick Park were being built.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Converted ballparks were an alternative to building an entirely new stadium.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] These parks were pre-existing minor league or college facility that were expanded to fit a major league team.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Converted ballparks are distinct from football stadia that were converted to multi-purpose parks in that converted ballparks were originally built for baseball only, albeit for a non-major league level.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Early converted ballparks were Memorial Stadium in Baltimore, Municipal Stadium in Kansas City, and Metropolitan Stadium in Bloomington, Minnesota.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] All three were expanded minor league facilities, although Baltimore and the Met were constructed with the idea of expanding to major league level in mind.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Kansas City was a true established minor league park that was substantially expanded to accommodate major league size crowds.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Temporary ballparks made a comeback in 2020, when Sahlen Field was used as a temporary MLB facility by the Toronto Blue Jays in the 2020 season and 2021 season due to Canada's travel restrictions following the outbreak of COVID-19, which prevented them from playing in the Rogers Centre.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Sutter Health Park is the temporary home of the Athletics from 2025 to 2027 leading up to the franchise's move to Las Vegas.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] After extensive damage to Tropicana Field by Hurricane Milton, it was announced that Steinbrenner Field will serve as the temporary home field for the Tampa Bay Rays during their 2025 season.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] These two types of ballpark are distinct because of their use, not their design.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/ballpark-p03] Because of this, a temporary or converted ballpark can also be any of the other types: jewel box, modern, multi-purpose, etc.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The college offered more than 40 undergraduate degree programs including nursing programs, a veterinary science program, and video game design and development programs.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Becker College has more than 21,000 alumni.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The institution comprised two separate campuses located six miles apart, each with its own residence halls, library, dining hall and academic facilities.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Becker's Leicester campus was home to Leicester Academy, founded in 1784.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The campus was situated within the town common, which in the 18th century, consisted of a tavern, a meetinghouse and the first home built in Leicester, now known as the May House.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Colonel Ebenezer Crafts of Sturbridge and Jacob Davis of Charlton saw a need to provide schooling for children of modest families who lived in Central Massachusetts.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The state legislature was petitioned, funds were raised and, in 1784, Leicester Academy was founded.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The charter was signed by Governor John Hancock, and Samuel Adams, President of the Massachusetts State Senate; major benefactors included Moses Gill, a future lieutenant governor.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] It was the third academy founded in post-independence Massachusetts, after the founding of Governor Dummer Academy at Byfield in 1782 and of Phillips Academy at Andover in 1778.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Crafts, son of the founder, Ephraim Allen of Sturbridge and Samuel Swan of Leicester were members of the inaugural class.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] All three later graduated from Harvard College.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The Leicester Academy became defunct in 1917.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] According to the Massachusetts Department of Higher Education, Leicester Academy existed until 1952, when it became Leicester Junior College.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Three years after the Leicester Academy centennial, in 1887, Becker's Business College was founded.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Edward Carl Anton (E.C.A.) Becker founded Becker College in Worcester, Massachusetts, in 1887 and served as its president from 1887 through 1907.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Becker was born in Peoria, Illinois, on April 30, 1855.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] He attended Peoria Bryant & Stratton Business College, graduating from both the business and telegraph departments.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Following graduation, he served as a teacher and principal at the college.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] He went on to purchase and manage the Rockford Business College in Rockford, Illinois, and the Freeport Business College in Elgin, Illinois.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] After Becker's successes in the Midwest, he moved east, managing a school in Pottsville, Pennsylvania, before arriving in Worcester to lead the business department at Hinman College.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In 1887 he established Becker's Business College in the Clark building at 492 Main Street in Worcester.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] By the end of the week 30 were in attendance.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The college offered courses in bookkeeping, penmanship, arithmetic, shorthand and typing for both men and women.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Becker was a member of the Worcester Board of Trade and the Worcester Economic Club.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In his free time he enjoyed hunting in Maine, a hobby showcased by two large moose heads that adorned the Becker reception office until the early 1930s.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] He was also known to have had a pleasant sense of humor.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Upon his death in 1907, the college had an average annual enrollment of 200 students.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Graduates excelled in the counting rooms of Worcester's manufacturing and mercantile establishments and on their civil service examinations.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Becker's wife Mary Charlotte Becker formed a corporation to manage the college, serving as treasurer, with son-in-law Walter S.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Doud as president, and daughter Eva M. as clerk.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In 1938 the Medical Secretarial course was introduced and became a national model that attracted a number of students.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] With a critical need for student housing in the area, in 1939 the college purchased a late-Victorian house, built in 1893 on Cedar Street.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] This home became the first Becker dormitory.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In 1974, Becker and Leicester began working together to expand academic offerings and provide broader social and recreational opportunities for their students.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] As a result of their close cooperation, the two were formally consolidated in 1977 as the Worcester campus and Leicester campus of Becker College.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Johnson assumed the presidency of the college.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In April 2011, the Commonwealth of Massachusetts designated Becker as the home of the Massachusetts Digital Games Institute (MassDiGI).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The Massachusetts Digital Games Institute (MassDiGI) was a statewide center, designated by the Commonwealth, for academic cooperation, entrepreneurship, and economic development across the Massachusetts digital and video games ecosystem.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In 2014, the college launched its first master's degree, a Master of Arts in mental health counseling.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The following year, the college signed a memorandum of understanding with Nobel Laureate Professor Muhammad Yunus to establish the Yunus Social Business Centre @ Becker College.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The centre was established in partnership with the Seven Hills Foundation and focused on identifying real-world social problems and creating innovative, self-sustaining solutions to transform lives and communities.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In May 2017, Becker College welcomed its 11th president, Nancy P.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In March 2021, Massachusetts Department of Higher Education said the college's financial situation had become "sufficiently uncertain" to threaten its long-term viability.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The statement added that the department "believes that the institution is unlikely to sustain full operations through the next academic year".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] A few weeks later, college trustees announced that the school would, indeed, close.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] They said that because of losses sustained during the COVID-19 pandemic, the college would have had to severely curtail its programs, sell assets and take on additional debt to stay open past the end of the spring 2021 semester.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In May 2021, the college announced plans to lay off 329 employees at the end of the 2020–2021 academic year, at which point it closed permanently.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Following the closure, nearby Clark University opened the Becker School of Design and Technology, carrying on Becker's globally recognized game design programs with many of the same faculty.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Becker offered more than 40 degree programs ranging from Animal Sciences and Criminal Justice and Game Design to Nursing and Veterinary Sciences.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Becker had a total of 419 faculty and staff, representing a 17:1 student/faculty ratio.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The college offered Bachelor, Associate, and Master Degree Programs.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In 2014 Becker College launched its first graduate degree - a Master of Arts in mental health counseling.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] A Master of Fine Arts in Interactive Media Design was also offered.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] All programs were fully accredited through the New England Commission of Higher Education (NECHE).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In 2016, 100% of Becker nursing students passed their Registered Nurses examination.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The game design program at Becker was consistently recognized on The Princeton Review's list of top undergraduate schools to study game design.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] In 2016, the program was ranked at number five.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] By the time the College closed in 2021, the program was ranked number two.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The Massachusetts Digital Games Institute (MassDiGI) was a statewide center, designated by the Commonwealth, for academic cooperation, entrepreneurship and economic development across the Massachusetts digital and video games ecosystem.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Established in 2011 and based at Becker College, MassDiGI was the result of creative collaboration among academia, industry and government, aimed at fostering the growth of the game industry and innovation economy.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] After Becker College closed in 2021, MassDigi continued to operate, from a new home at the nearby Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Both campuses occupy historic districts with buildings listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The Worcester campus was located on Sever Street in the residential Elm Park neighborhood, not far from downtown Worcester, which is about 40 miles west of Boston.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Purchased in 1854 using public funds, Elm Park is recognized as one of the first purchases of land for a public park in the United States.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The campus area belonged to the Lincoln family (noted for governors Levi Lincoln Sr. and Levi Lincoln Jr., and much of it is in the Lincoln Estate-Elm Park Historic District, which includes some historic properties owned by the college.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The Leicester campus was adjacent to the historic center of that town, and a number of buildings on that campus are included in the Washburn Square-Leicester Common Historic District.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Weller Academic Building (former site of the Bancroft School) and the Health Science Center on the Sever Street Quad, as well as in the Design Center (Graphic, Interior and Game) on Cedar Street, which also houses a Mac Lab and motion-capture suite.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] A multi-purpose gymnasium and dining hall are features of the Gilbert R.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Boutin Student Center, and within three blocks on Cedar Street are six of the 11 residence halls found on the Worcester campus, Merrill, Davis, Lincoln, Colton (Becker's first residence hall in Worcester, purchased in 1939), Cedar, and Willow Hall, a brick apartment-style building.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Beeches, Miller, Maple, and Bullock Halls also serve dormitories.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Lining Roxbury Street are office buildings, campus police and the Collaborative Learning Center, in former homes and typical "three-deckers" for which Worcester is famous.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] On Worcester's quad is a monument commemorating the pitching of the first perfect game in professional baseball, on June 12, 1880, by Lee Richmond of Worcester, against Cleveland, in a National League game.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The game took place on the Worcester Agricultural Fairgrounds, where the college, and much of the neighborhood, now stands.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The Leicester campus was in a traditional, rural setting, located six miles west of Worcester.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Students are shuttled between Leicester and Worcester for classes and events.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The historic Leicester Common was a centerpiece to the campus, which includes three historic buildings, once stately homes that the college transitioned into residence halls, Lane, Winslow and Hitchcock.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Behind those halls, on Old Main Street, are the Leicester gymnasium and the Lenfest Animal Health Center, the college's veterinary teaching clinic, which was open to the public for appointments during the academic year.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Around "the grove" are the Borger Academic Center which houses classrooms, laboratories and the Daniels Hall auditorium, Marsh Hall (classrooms, offices and the Collaborative Learning Center); Susan E.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Knight Hall (dining hall, rooms and offices) and the Leicester Student Center.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The Leicester campus was also home to many of the college's athletic teams that play home games on Alumni Field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The equestrian team practice and host competitions at the Becker Equestrian Center in nearby Paxton, Massachusetts, and the hockey team host home games at the New England Sports Center in Marlborough, Massachusetts.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] One of the most prominent buildings on the former Leicester campus was the Rev.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Samuel May House, built in 1835 and officially recognized in 2008 as a stop on the Underground Railroad.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Samuel May was a leading anti-slavery figure for over three decades and a prominent individual in the New England literary community during the mid-1800s.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] His wife was a member of the Daughters of the American Revolution (DAR) as well as an outspoken proponent for women's suffrage.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Frequent visitors to the May House included Ralph Waldo Emerson, William Lloyd Garrison, Booker T.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Washington, George Hoar, May's brother-in-law, Bronson Alcott, and his daughter Louisa May Alcott.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] It is known that the young author spent summers at the May House and it has been reported that she wrote some of her works from her room on the third floor.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The house currently serves as a residence hall.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The college broke ground in the spring 2011 on a new campus center in Leicester.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Fuller Campus Center was opened in September 2012.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The new building was adjacent to the previous student center and houses a dining hall and fitness center as well as academic, office, and social spaces.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Becker College offered equine academic programs, a competitive equestrian team for Becker College students, boarding, and lessons for the public at the Becker College Equestrian Center, located in Paxton, Massachusetts.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] A teaching facility which includes a veterinary clinic that can see clients for wellness care and non-urgent medical and surgical care for dogs, cats, other small mammals, and birds, located on the Leicester campus.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] A teaching facility that gives students the opportunity to assess a crime scene, in terms of understanding the nature of physical evidence, located on the Worcester campus.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Becker College once fielded 17 intercollegiate athletic teams that competed in the Division III level of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Prior to becoming an NCAA institution in the fall of 1998, Becker competed in junior college athletics.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The 2007–08 women's basketball team was the first team to qualify for the NCAA tournament.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The soccer, tennis, field hockey, golf, basketball, baseball, volleyball and softball teams competed in the New England Collegiate Conference (NECC).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The football team was a member of the Commonwealth Coast Conference (CCC).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Men's ice hockey was an associate member of the CCC.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Women's lacrosse was a member of the New England Women's Lacrosse Alliance (NEWLA).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] Men's lacrosse was an associate member of the NECC.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The equestrian team was a member of the Intercollegiate Horse Show Association (IHSA/ Zone 1, Region 1).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/becker-college] The women's ice hockey team, which was introduced in the fall of 2014, was a member of Eastern College Athletic Conference Northeast (ECAC).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The **Boston Braves** were a Major League Baseball team that played in Boston for the National League from 1871 to 1952.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The team relocated to Milwaukee after the 1952 season, becoming the Milwaukee Braves, and subsequently moved to Atlanta in 1966.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] During its 82-year stay in Massachusetts, the franchise was known by various nicknames, including the **Red Stockings**, **Red Caps**, **Beaneaters**, **Rustlers**, **Bees**, and "Braves".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Their longest-lasting nickname was inspired by Tamanend, a chief of the Lenni-Lenape in the Delaware Valley.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] While in Boston, the team won 10 National League pennants and a World Series championship in 1914 that came after a season in which the Braves were in last place as late as July 15—a turnaround that led to the nickname "Miracle Braves".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] In 1948, the Braves reached the World Series largely as a result of their two dominant pitchers, Warren Spahn and Johnny Sain, who inspired the *Boston Post* slogan "Spahn and Sain and pray for rain." The Braves posted a losing record in all but 12 of the 38 seasons after their World Series win.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Boston franchise played at South End Grounds from 1871 to 1914 and at Braves Field from 1915 to 1952.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Braves Field is now Nickerson Field of Boston University.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The franchise, from Boston to Milwaukee to Atlanta, is the oldest continuously operating professional baseball franchise.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Boston Braves had an overall win–loss record of 5,118–5,598–138 (.478) during their 77-year major-league tenure in Boston.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Six former Boston Braves players have been elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Cincinnati Red Stockings, established in 1869 as the first openly all-professional baseball team, voted to dissolve after the 1870 season.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Player-manager Harry Wright then went to Boston, Massachusetts—at the invitation of Boston businessman Ivers Whitney Adams—with brother George Wright and two other Cincinnati players joined the **Boston Red Stockings**, a charter member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] This team and its successors are the oldest continuously playing team in American professional sports.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Led by the Wright brothers, Barnes, and Spalding, the Red Stockings won four of the National Association's five championships.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The team became one of the National League's charter franchises in 1876, sometimes called the "**Red Caps**" (as a new Cincinnati Red Stockings club was another charter member).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Boston came to be called the **Beaneaters** by sportswriters in 1883, while retaining red as the team color.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Red Caps/Beaneaters won eight pennants during the 19th century.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Their manager was Frank Selee, the first manager not to double as a player as well.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The 1898 team finished 102–47, a club record for wins that would stand for almost a century.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] In 1894 the Braves became the first major league baseball team to wear letterforms on their uniform caps when they added a monogram-style device to their front.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] In 1897, the Beaneaters, as runner-up in the National League, took part in the 1897 Temple Cup championship series against the Baltimore Orioles, losing in five games.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] They only managed one winning season from 1900 to 1913, and lost 100 or more games six times.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] In 1907, the renamed Doves (temporarily) eliminated the red from their stockings because their manager thought the red dye could cause wounds to become infected (as noted in *The Sporting News Baseball Guide* during the 1940s when each team's entry had a history of its nickname(s).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] See details in History of baseball team nicknames).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The American League club's owner, Charles Taylor, changed his team's name to the Red Sox in place of the "Americans".
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] When George and John Dovey acquired the club in 1907, the team was named the **Doves**; when purchased by William Hepburn Russell in 1911 reporters tried out **Rustlers.** The team adopted an official name, the **Braves**, for the first time in 1912.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Their owner, James Gaffney, a member of New York City's Tammany Hall, tributed the team to Tamanend, "The Patron Saint of America," with the name and his image as the logo.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Two years later, the Braves put together one of the most memorable seasons in baseball history.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] After a dismal 4–18 start, the Braves seemed to be on pace for a last place finish.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] On July 4, 1914, the Braves lost both games of a doubleheader to the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The consecutive losses put their record at 26–40 and the Braves were in last place, 15 games behind the league-leading New York Giants, who had won the previous three league pennants.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] After a day off, the Braves put together a hot streak, and from July 6 through September 5, the Braves won 41 games against only 12 losses.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] On September 7 and 8, the Braves took 2 of 3 from the New York Giants and moved into first place.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Braves tore through September and early October, closing with 25 wins against 6 losses, while the Giants went 16–16.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] They are the only team to win a pennant after being in last place on the Fourth of July.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] They were in last place as late as July 18, but were close to the pack, moving into fourth on July 21 and second place on August 12.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Despite their comeback, the Braves entered the World Series as a heavy underdog to Connie Mack's Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Nevertheless, the Braves swept the Athletics—the first unqualified sweep in the young history of the modern World Series (the 1907 World Series had one tied game)—to win the world championship.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Meanwhile, former Chicago Cubs infielder Johnny Evers, in his second season with the Braves, won the Chalmers Award.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Braves played the World Series (as well as the last few weeks of the 1914 regular season) at Fenway Park, since their normal home, the South End Grounds, was too small.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] However, the Braves' success inspired owner Gaffney to build a modern park, Braves Field, which opened in August 1915.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] It was the largest park in the majors at the time, with 40,000 seats and also a very spacious outfield.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The park was novel for its time; public transportation brought fans right into the park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] After contending for most of 1915 and 1916, the Braves spent much of the next 19 years in mediocrity, during which they posted only three winning seasons (1921, 1933, and 1934).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The lone highlight of those years came when Giants' attorney Emil Fuchs bought the team in 1923 to bring his longtime friend, pitching great Christy Mathewson, back into the game.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Although original plans called for Mathewson to be the principal owner, he had never recovered from tuberculosis that he had contracted after being gassed during World War I.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] By the end of the 1923 season, it was obvious Mathewson could not continue even in a reduced role, and he would die two years later, with the result that Fuchs was permanently given the presidency.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] In 1928, the Braves traded for Hall of Famer Rogers Hornsby who had a very productive year in his only season with Boston.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] He batted .387 to win his seventh and final batting championship.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Fuchs was committed to building a winner, but the damage from the years before his arrival took some time to overcome.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Braves finally managed to compete in 1933 and 1934 under manager Bill McKechnie, but Fuchs' revenue was severely depleted due to the Great Depression.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Looking for a way to get more supporters and more money, Fuchs worked out a deal with the New York Yankees to acquire Babe Ruth, who had, coincidentally, started his career with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Fuchs named Ruth vice president and assistant manager of the Braves, and promised him a share of team profits.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] He was also to be consulted on all player transactions.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Fuchs even suggested that Ruth, who had long had his heart set on managing, could take over as manager once McKechnie stepped down—perhaps as early as 1936.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] At first, it looked like Ruth was the final piece the team needed in 1935.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] On opening day, he had a hand in all of the Braves' runs in a 4–2 win over the Giants.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Opening Day proved to be the only time the Braves were over .500 all year.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] A 4–20 May ended any realistic chance of contention.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] At the same time, it became apparent that Ruth was finished even as a part-time player.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] While his high living of previous years had begun catching up with him a year earlier, his conditioning rapidly declined in the first month of 1935.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] While he was still able to hit at first, he could do little else.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] He could no longer run, and his fielding was so terrible that three of the Braves' pitchers threatened to go on strike if Ruth were in the lineup.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Ruth soon discovered that he was vice president and assistant manager in name only, and Fuchs' promise of a share of team profits was hot air.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] In fact, Ruth discovered that Fuchs expected him to invest some of *his* money in the team.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Seeing a franchise in complete disarray, Ruth retired on June 1, only six days after he clouted what turned out to be the last three home runs of his career, in what remains one of the most memorable afternoons in baseball history.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] He had wanted to quit as early as May 12, but Fuchs wanted him to hang on so he could play in every National League park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] By this time, the Braves were 9–27, their season all but over.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] They ultimately finished 38–115, easily the worst season in franchise history.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Their .248 winning percentage is tied for the seventh-worst in baseball history, and the sixth-worst in National League history.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] It is the second-worst in modern baseball history (behind only the 1916 Philadelphia Athletics), and the worst in modern National League history.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Insolvent like his team, Fuchs was forced to give up control of the Braves in August 1935.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The principal financial backer for the team, Charles F.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Adams, was banned by Commissioner Landis from taking control of the team because Adams owned Suffolk Downs race track.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Quinn did not care for the Braves name, possibly because it was linked to former owner Gaffney and to New York's Tammany Hall politics and launched a contest for the general public with the regional sportswriters being the judges.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Among 13,000 votes of 1,327 potential names, the team was renamed to the **Boston Bees** Keeping up with the Bees theme, Braves Field became nicknamed the Bee Hive.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] This did little to change the team's fortunes.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] After five uneven years, a new owner, construction magnate Lou Perini, changed the nickname back to the Braves.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] In 1948, the team won the National League pennant by capturing 91 games to finish 61⁄2 places ahead of the second–place St.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] They also attracted 1,455,439 fans to Braves Field, the third-largest gate in the National League and a high-water mark for the team's stay in Boston.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The pitching staff was anchored by Hall of Famer Warren Spahn and Johnny Sain, who won 39 games between them.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The poem received such a wide audience that the sentiment, usually now paraphrased as "Spahn, Sain, then pray for rain" or "Spahn, Sain and two days of rain", entered the baseball vocabulary.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Ironically, in the 1948 season, the Braves actually had a better record in games that Spahn and Sain *did not* start than in games they did.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Braves lost the 1948 World Series in six games to the Cleveland Indians (who had beaten the Red Sox in a tie-breaker game to spoil an all-Boston World Series).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] This turned out to be the Braves' last hurrah in Boston.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Acquired earlier by trade from the Brooklyn Dodgers, on April 18, 1950, Sam "Jet" Jethroe was added to the Boston Braves roster.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Dodgers had another young CF in Duke Snider rising in their system, resulting in the trade to the Braves.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Going on to be named National League Rookie of the Year at age 32, Jethroe broke the color barrier with Boston.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] In 1950, Jethroe hit .273 with 100 runs, 18 home runs and 58 RBI.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] His 35 stolen bases led the National League, a feat he would duplicate in 1951.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] While in Boston, Jethroe was a roommate of Chuck Cooper, of the Boston Celtics who was the first African-American player drafted by an NBA team.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] A former Negro leagues star and military veteran, Jethroe remains the oldest player to have won Rookie of the Year honors.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Amid four mediocre seasons after 1948, attendance steadily dwindled, even though Braves Field had the reputation of being more family friendly than Fenway.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] For a half century, the major leagues had not had a single franchise move.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Braves played their last home game in Boston on September 21, 1952, losing to the Brooklyn Dodgers 8–2 before 8,822 at Braves Field; the home attendance for the 1952 season was under 282,000.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] On March 13, 1953, owner Lou Perini said that he would seek permission from the National League to move the Braves to Milwaukee, Wisconsin.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] After the franchise's long history in Boston, the day became known as "Black Friday" in the city as fans mourned the team's exit after eight decades.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Perini, however, pointed to dwindling attendance as the main reason for the move.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] He also announced that he had recently bought out his original partners.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] He announced Milwaukee as that was where the Braves had their top farm club, the Brewers.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Milwaukee had long been a possible target for moving.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Louis Browns there earlier the same year (Milwaukee was the original home of that franchise), but his proposal had been voted down by the other American League owners.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Going into spring training in 1953, it appeared that the Braves would play another year in Boston unless the National League gave permission for the move.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] After a 31⁄2-hour meeting at the Vinoy Park Hotel in St.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] Petersburg, Florida, league approval was granted after Perini promised not to sell the team.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] During a game against the New York Yankees on March 18, the sale was announced final and that the team would move to Milwaukee, immediately.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The All-Star Game had been scheduled for Braves Field.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] It was moved to Crosley Field and hosted by the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Braves franchise moved their triple-A Brewers from Milwaukee to Toledo, Ohio.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] After the Braves moved to Milwaukee in 1953, the Braves Field site was sold to Boston University and reconstructed as Nickerson Field, the home of many Boston University teams.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/boston-braves-baseball] The Braves Field scoreboard was sold to the Kansas City A's and used at Municipal Stadium; the A's moved to Oakland after the 1967 season.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] The site was bounded by Highland Street (north), Sever Street (east), Cedar Street (south), and Agricultural (later Russell) Street (west).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] The grounds were just east of the large public park called Elm Park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] Today, the former fairgrounds property contains a grid of streets, and many homes and businesses, including the now closed Becker College.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] The Fairgrounds were home to an agricultural fair and to a horse trotting track, usually called the Driving Park.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] "Driving" was a commonly used synonym for trotting, long before the term came to be associated primarily with the not-yet-invented automobile.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] The Driving Park opened in May 1872, and hosted baseball by August of that year.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] Horse racing at the grounds took place as late as July 1894, but appears to have ceased after that time due to local officials disallowing "pool-selling" (gambling) on races.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] Driving Park hosted some professional baseball games prior to Worcester acquiring its own franchise.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] These included an exhibition between the National Association (NA) pennant winner Boston Red Stockings and runner-up Philadelphia Whites, played on October 30, 1873, after the end of the season—Boston prevailed, 15–9, before a crowd of 2,000.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] A regular-season NA contest was held at Driving Park on October 30, 1874, between Boston and the Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] Hartford won, 17–11, in front of a crowd of 500.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] The Worcester Worcesters competed in 1879 in a later National Association (unrelated to the earlier NA), then for three seasons, 1880 to 1882, in the major-league National League (NL).
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] On June 12, 1880, Worcester pitcher Lee Richmond threw the first perfect game in major-league history.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] There is a granite post commemorating the perfect game on the former Becker College campus.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] The park was also the site of the first, true major league doubleheader.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] For the price of a single game, Worcester fans saw two games against the Providence Grays on September 25, 1882.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] The last game for the local major-league club was played on September 29, 1882, with Troy defeating Worcester, 10–7.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] But it was not the last major-league game in Worcester; five years later, on August 17, 1887, the fairgrounds hosted an NL game between Washington and Boston.
[src:worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds/worcester-agricultural-fairgrounds] The contest—to make up a previously postponed game in the District of Columbia—was played in Worcester at the recommendation of Washington manager John Gaffney, who had grown up in Worcester.
